  <span id="freeText16947857381531672817" style="display:none">Excellent historical fiction on a subject that most people don't know a lot about. After the end of the Civil War, blacks and poor whites began to cooperate and build communities together. They managed to pool their resources to buy small farms and started schools. There were even blacks who served in Congress. But some people felt threatened by that. <br /><br />In 1876, there was a close election between Rutherford B. Hayes, a Republican (back when the Republicans were still the party of Lincoln) and Samuel J. Tilden, a Democrat (when the Democrats were the party of slavery). The election was very close, in large part because election results were being tampered with such that the votes of the blacks and poor whites weren't being counted--similar to today. As a compromise, the Southern Democrats agreed to accept the presidency of Rutherford B. Hayes in exchange for the Northern troops pulling out of the South.<br /><br />Once the Northern troops had departed, there was nothing to stop the Ku Klux Klan (backed by the wealthy Southerners) from terrorizing the blacks and the poor whites who were cooperating with them. The Jim Crow laws were passed and blacks did not attain a comparable level of freedom for 100 years with the advent of the Civil Rights movement.<br /><br />Freedom Road tells that story from the perspective of one such community. Worth a read!</span>
